const transcript={dataset_id:'ds001_aml',model_id:'gpt-5-codex',harness_id:'codex-cli-local-analysis',max_iterations:25,iterations:it};fs.writeFileSync('transcript.json',JSON.stringify(transcript,null,2));
const summary="'`Oncology dataset ds001_aml analysis summary

Rows analyzed: ${N}. Outcome: objective_response. Overall response rate was ${fmtPct(stats.overall_y)}.

Main-effect exploration found a favorable unadjusted association for npm1_mutation: ${fmtPct(stats.npm1.p1)} response with mutation versus ${fmtPct(stats.npm1.p0)} without it, a ${round(stats.npm1.d*100,1)} percentage-point difference (p=${fmtP(stats.npm1.p)}). Adverse genetics moved in the opposite direction: tp53_mutation was associated with a ${round(stats.tp53.d*100,1)} percentage-point lower response rate (p=${fmtP(stats.tp53.p)}), and complex_karyotype with a ${round(stats.complex.d*100,1)} percentage-point lower response rate (p=${fmtP(stats.complex.p)}).

Clinical burden variables were consistent with lower response. In the adjusted linear-probability model, each 1-point increase in ecog_ps was associated with ${round(stats.ecog.b*100,1)} percentage points lower response (p=${fmtP(stats.ecog.p)}), each 1% greater weight_loss_pct_6mo with ${round(stats.weight.b*100,2)} percentage points lower response (p=${fmtP(stats.weight.p)}), blast_pct_marrow with ${round(stats.blast.b*100,2)} percentage points per percentage point (p=${fmtP(stats.blast.p)}), and wbc_k_per_ul with ${round(stats.wbc.b*100,3)} percentage points per k/uL (p=${fmtP(stats.wbc.p)}). Albumin was favorable (${round(stats.albumin.b*100,1)} percentage points per g/dL, p=${fmtP(stats.albumin.p)}), while CRP was unfavorable (${round(stats.crp.b*100,3)} percentage points per mg/L, p=${fmtP(stats.crp.p)}). Age and sex_female were not statistically significant after adjustment (age p=${fmtP(stats.age.p)}, sex_female p=${fmtP(stats.sex.p)}).

Initial treatment scans showed higher unadjusted response with treatment_venetoclax_azacitidine (${fmtPct(stats.ven.p1)} vs ${fmtPct(stats.ven.p0)}, difference ${round(stats.ven.d*100,1)} percentage points, p=${fmtP(stats.ven.p)}) and in patients marked unfit_for_intensive (${fmtPct(stats.unfit.p1)} vs ${fmtPct(stats.unfit.p0)}, difference ${round(stats.unfit.d*100,1)} percentage points, p=${fmtP(stats.unfit.p)}). A main-effects adjusted model preserved positive coefficients for npm1_mutation (${round(stats.adj_npm1.b,4)}), unfit_for_intensive (${round(stats.adj_unfit.b,4)}), and treatment_venetoclax_azacitidine (${round(stats.adj_ven.b,4)}), but later interaction testing showed these main effects were incomplete summaries.

Targeted therapy hypotheses outside venetoclax-azacitidine were not supported. flt3_itd and flt3_tkd had no meaningful unadjusted response advantage. The adjusted treatment_midostaurin by flt3_itd interaction was ${round(stats.mid_flt3.b,4)} (p=${fmtP(stats.mid_flt3.p)}). treatment_gilteritinib interactions with flt3_itd and flt3_tkd were ${round(stats.gilt_flt3.b,4)} and ${round(stats.gilt_tkd.b,4)} (p=${fmtP(stats.gilt_flt3.p)} and ${fmtP(stats.gilt_tkd.p)}). IDH-directed hypotheses were also refuted: treatment_ivosidenib by idh1_mutation was ${round(stats.ivo_idh1.b,4)} (p=${fmtP(stats.ivo_idh1.p)}) and treatment_enasidenib by idh2_mutation was ${round(stats.ena_idh2.b,4)} (p=${fmtP(stats.ena_idh2.p)}).

The dominant pattern was treatment-biomarker-fitness heterogeneity for treatment_venetoclax_azacitidine. In unfit_for_intensive patients, venetoclax-azacitidine was associated with a ${round(stats.ven_unfit_pos.d*100,1)} percentage-point response increase (${fmtPct(stats.ven_unfit_pos.p1)} vs ${fmtPct(stats.ven_unfit_pos.p0)}, p=${fmtP(stats.ven_unfit_pos.p)}), but not in fit patients (difference ${round(stats.ven_unfit_neg.d*100,1)} percentage points, p=${fmtP(stats.ven_unfit_neg.p)}). In npm1_mutation patients, the venetoclax-azacitidine difference was ${round(stats.ven_npm1_pos.d*100,1)} percentage points (p=${fmtP(stats.ven_npm1_pos.p)}), but it was near zero in NPM1-wild-type patients. Adjusted two-way interactions were strongly positive for venetoclax-azacitidine with unfit_for_intensive (${round(stats.ven_unfit.b,4)}) and npm1_mutation (${round(stats.ven_npm1.b,4)}), and negative with tp53_mutation (${round(stats.ven_tp53.b,4)}) and complex_karyotype (${round(stats.ven_complex.b,4)}).

Refinement showed the apparent two-way venetoclax-azacitidine signals were best explained by a three-way interaction. Among patients with both npm1_mutation and unfit_for_intensive, venetoclax-azacitidine response was ${fmtPct(stats.ven_npm1_unfit.p1)} versus ${fmtPct(stats.ven_npm1_unfit.p0)} without venetoclax-azacitidine, a ${round(stats.ven_npm1_unfit.d*100,1)} percentage-point difference (p=${fmtP(stats.ven_npm1_unfit.p)}). The corresponding differences were small and nonsignificant in NPM1-mutated fit patients (${round(stats.ven_npm1_fit.d*100,1)} percentage points, p=${fmtP(stats.ven_npm1_fit.p)}) and NPM1-wild-type unfit patients (${round(stats.ven_non_npm1_unfit.d*100,1)} percentage points, p=${fmtP(stats.ven_non_npm1_unfit.p)}). The explicit three-way coefficient treatment_venetoclax_azacitidine * npm1_mutation * unfit_for_intensive was ${round(stats.triple.b,4)} (p=${fmtP(stats.triple.p)}).

Adverse-risk genetics modified those favorable NPM1/venetoclax patterns. The NPM1 advantage was present without tp53_mutation (${round(stats.npm1_no_tp53.d*100,1)} percentage points, p=${fmtP(stats.npm1_no_tp53.p)}) but absent with tp53_mutation (${round(stats.npm1_tp53_pos.d*100,1)} percentage points, p=${fmtP(stats.npm1_tp53_pos.p)}), with an NPM1 by TP53 interaction of ${round(stats.npm1_tp53.b,4)} (p=${fmtP(stats.npm1_tp53.p)}). Similarly, NPM1 was favorable without complex_karyotype (${round(stats.npm1_complex_neg.d*100,1)} percentage points, p=${fmtP(stats.npm1_complex_neg.p)}) but not with complex_karyotype (${round(stats.npm1_complex_pos.d*100,1)} percentage points, p=${fmtP(stats.npm1_complex_pos.p)}), with an interaction coefficient of ${round(stats.npm1_complex.b,4)} (p=${fmtP(stats.npm1_complex.p)}). Within NPM1-mutated unfit patients, venetoclax-azacitidine produced a very large benefit when TP53 was wild-type (${round(stats.triple_tp53_neg.d*100,1)} percentage points, p=${fmtP(stats.triple_tp53_neg.p)}) or karyotype was non-complex (${round(stats.triple_complex_neg.d*100,1)} percentage points, p=${fmtP(stats.triple_complex_neg.p)}), but not when tp53_mutation or complex_karyotype was present.

For treatment_7plus3, there was no adjusted overall response association (${round(stats.adj_7plus3.b,4)}, p=${fmtP(stats.adj_7plus3.p)}), and the treatment_7plus3 by complex_karyotype interaction was negative (${round(stats.seven_complex.b,4)}, p=${fmtP(stats.seven_complex.p)}). Overall, the cohort'"'s most clinically meaningful signal is a high-response subgroup defined by treatment_venetoclax_azacitidine plus npm1_mutation plus unfit_for_intensive, conditional on absence of TP53 mutation and complex karyotype. FLT3- and IDH-directed treatment-biomarker hypotheses were not statistically supported in this dataset."'`;
